    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c4912a; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:300; line-height:1.2; color:#1c1917; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">The inner north-western suburb that families and first home buyers pursue for its creek-side amenity, defence community character, and an address that delivers the inner north-west lifestyle at a more accessible price point than Ashgrove or Bardon.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Enoggera sits approximately seven kilometres north-west of the Brisbane CBD, tucked inside the ring road in a corridor where Ashgrove, Bardon and Red Hill have commanded significant premiums for well over a decade. The suburb occupies a distinct position in this market: it delivers the same general lifestyle offer as its more celebrated neighbours without the price barrier that has moved many families and first home buyers further out. Enoggera Creek and its associated greenway run through the area, providing a linear park corridor that residents value and that the suburb's address does not always get credit for. Buyers who find their way here in 2026 have typically been doing genuine suburb comparisons and arrived at Enoggera after concluding that the value on offer is real.
    </p>
