    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The defence precinct nearby has shaped a particular community fabric in Enoggera. Defence-affiliated families bring consistent, purpose-driven demand to the local market: they are buyers who prioritise school catchments, practical family homes, and an address within reasonable proximity of the base. This buyer cohort has underpinned steady activity in the suburb across economic cycles, and sellers who understand this profile can prepare and position their property to speak directly to what these buyers require. First home buyers represent a second significant demand layer, drawn by the price point relative to Ashgrove and Bardon and motivated by the prospect of an inner north-western address within a sensible first purchase budget.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The housing stock in Enoggera is a mix of post-war homes and character Queenslanders, with a smaller number of newer builds. Properties that sit on workable blocks with usable outdoor space and good street presentation consistently attract the strongest buyer competition. The suburb's internal streets retain a settled, owner-occupied residential character that buyers recognise when they walk them, and that character is part of what they are purchasing when they choose this address.
    </p>
